Now I can see that `GenericResourceData.Serialization.cs` uses `#if NET6_0_OR_GREATER` with `writer.WriteRawValue(Properties)` and the else branch uses `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, document.RootElement)`. Since we're targeting net9.0, the `#if NET6_0_OR_GREATER` branch will be taken, so those `document.RootElement` usages in the `#else` block won't actually compile. But wait, looking more closely:```csharp
#if NET6_0_OR_GREATER
    writer.WriteRawValue(Properties);


#else
    using (JsonDocument document = JsonDocument.Parse(Properties, ModelSerializationExtensions.JsonDocumentOptions))
    {
        JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, document.RootElement);
    }
#endif
```This one won't trigger warnings on net9.0 since the `#else` branch isn't compiled. Good. But many other files do NOT have the `#if` guard. For example, in `ManagementGroup/Generated/Models/CreateManagementGroupDetails.Serialization.cs`, the `JsonSerializer.Serialize(writer, document.RootElement)` is NOT inside a `#if` block, which means it will actually compile and cause the warning.

Let me double-check the actual warning output to see which lines are really problematic. Looking back at the warnings for GenericResourceData, I see them at lines 45, 77, 142, 179, 211, and 254 — line 55 is inside an `#else` block so it wouldn't be compiled anyway. The actual pattern causing issues is when the code iterates through serialized additional raw data and writes raw values, typically guarded by a format check but not always protected by the conditional compilation directives. they're only triggering warnings in the net9.0 code path, not in the `#else` blocks that don't get compiled. Let me examine one of these specific cases to see what's different.

